<dl id="n35232c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n35" href="#n35232c">N35 (VI.B.24)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n35all.htm#n35232c"> 232(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> chantry <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n35232c"><li>FW 533.16 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n35232c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n35232c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n35232c">MS BL 47484b-358</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:088 <a name="rBd12" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd12">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd12.htm#n35232c">Draft: III&sect;3B.12</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The fraternity or guild was further empowered to found a <mark>chantry</mark>. This chantry was to consist of four priests who should celebrate Divine service daily for the welfare of the King, the Lord Deputy, the founders of the Guild and the brethren and sisters of the Guild during life, and after death for the repose of their souls and the souls of all the faithful departed. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The term &ldquo;chantry&rdquo; implies that the service, or portion of it, was sung. <small> John J. Webb, <a name="JJWG" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JJWG"><cite title="source">The Guilds of Dublin</cite></a> (Jun 1929) 15</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also: <a name="sa0061m" href="saall.htm#sa0061m">SA (VI.A):0061(m)</a> and <a name="n35043a" href="n35all.htm#n35043a">N35 (VI.B.24):043(a)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
